  <static seed="1078" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FunctionBasics/Functions200.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the domain of <m>\displaystyle{h}</m> where <m>\displaystyle{h(x)={\frac{2x}{x+4}}}</m>.</p>
<p><fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(-\infty ,-4\right)\cup \left(-4,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Since we are not allowed to divide by zero, the denominator of <m>h</m> cannot be zero. If <m>x</m> takes on the value <m>-4</m> then the denominator will equal zero.  So <m>x</m> can be any number but <m>-4</m>.   Therefore the domain of <m>h</m> is <m>{\left(-\infty ,-4\right)\cup \left(-4,\infty \right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
